  "text": "The InventoryConsumer implementation follows Apache Kafka ecosystem patterns established in the official Kafka codebase. The primary reference is the official Consumer example (examples/src/main/java/kafka/examples/Consumer.java), which demonstrates the standard consumer loop pattern. Key configuration patterns are defined in ConsumerConfig.java, which provides constants for all configuration keys rather than string literals. The implementation uses ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, ConsumerConfig.KEY_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, ConsumerConfig.VALUE_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG, and ConsumerConfig.AUTO_OFFSET_RESET_CONFIG to configure the consumer. The consumer loop pattern from KafkaConsumer.java uses the poll(Duration) API, which takes a Duration parameter (such as Duration.ofSeconds(1)) rather than the deprecated poll(long) method. After processing each batch of records obtained from ConsumerRecords, the implementation calls commitSync() to synchronously commit offsets, ensuring at-least-once delivery semantics. Error handling follows KafkaConsumer's documented pattern for WakeupException, which is thrown when wakeup() is called to interrupt the consumer, enabling graceful shutdown. The wakeup() method is thread-safe and allows shutdown signals from other threads. The implementation uses a volatile boolean flag to coordinate shutdown and passes WakeupException handling into the consumer loop, catching it only when shutdown is requested. This pattern is documented in the KafkaConsumer class documentation and exemplified in the Consumer.java example class. For idempotent processing, the implementation processes messages using the record offset and partition information available from ConsumerRecord, allowing idempotency keys to be derived from message metadata. The OffsetCommitCallback interface documents how commits are coordinated with the broker to prevent duplicate processing."
}

